"Abstract The recent Stanford Case, (the facts of which read like the front page of a tabloid), clarifies how one particular area of the Act, regarding the interception of communications transmitted by means of a private telecommunications system, requires to be interpreted. This clarification should help both private and public sector business understand this part of the Act better and adjust any communications policy they have accordingly. The case also explodes a few myths regarding the power of IT administrators and how they may exercise their broad access rights."
